{"key":"post-9466028","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9466028</id>\n<content>The problem with cubes is they often fruit so easily that they teach bad habits.&amp;nbsp; Many (sub)strains will fruit in complete darkness with no fresh air at all.&amp;nbsp; However, I know of very few mushroom growers that only grow cubes for more than a few projects before they get bored and want to move on.&amp;nbsp; Look at them as a training species for bigger and better things, thus instead of doing the minimum to get a few fruits, you perfect techniques to get wall to wall harvests of big beautiful fruits.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;With the experience you gain, you can then move on to edibles and/or harder to grow species and you'll have the background to succeed.&amp;nbsp; After all, you don't see too many adults riding bicycles with training wheels.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9467243</next>\n<prev>9465861</prev>\n<first>9463086</first>\n<last>9467275</last>\n<when>1229787245</when>\n<utime>12/20/08 05:34 PM</utime>\n</post>"}